{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fe7c168e-326c-48f9-b171-9ca263b23214","content":"The root cause is clear from the report: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation on every CLI invocation**. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild host in memory. Here's how to close that gap:\n\n### 1. Skip implicit restore (`--no-restore`)\nEvery `dotnet build` runs NuGet restore first. If packages haven't changed:\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nThis alone can shave ~1s off each invocation.\n\n### 2. Use the MSBuild Server\n.NET 8 supports a persistent MSBuild server process (like what VS does). Ensure it's enabled:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build\n```\nOr set it in the project:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <UseMSBuildServer>true</UseMSBuildServer>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\nThis keeps the MSBuild engine warm between builds, eliminating cold-start overhead.\n\n### 3. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nFor rapid edit-build-test cycles, `dotnet watch` keeps the build host alive and rebuilds on file change:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 4. Produce reference assemblies (multi-project)\nIf this project is referenced by others, adding this avoids recompiling dependents when only implementation (not API) changes:\n```xml\n<ProduceReferenceAssembly>true</ProduceReferenceAssembly>\n```\n\n### Recommended priority\nFor the complaint described (2-4s no-op builds), **`--no-restore` + MSBuild Server** will have the biggest impact, bringing CLI builds close to VS speed. `dotnet watch` is the best long-term workflow change for the inner loop.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1a65ff22-5abb-46c4-a46d-1edecc45a54d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is about **why** Visual Studio is faster: VS uses the MSBuild Server (a long-lived background process) that keeps the MSBuild engine warm, avoiding process startup and project re-evaluation costs on every build.\n\nThe .NET SDK (since .NET 8 / MSBuild 17.9+) supports the MSBuild Server for CLI builds too, but it's not always enabled by default (it was opt-in in earlier versions and has been progressively rolled out).\n\n\nI can apply the same MSBuild Server approach to the CLI by setting the environment variable or project property to enable it, which eliminates the cold-start penalty. For the development loop, `dotnet watch` keeps the build host alive and automatically triggers incremental builds on file changes. I should also look into enabling the MSBuild graph build to optimize how dependencies are evaluated.\n\nThe key insight is that .NET 8+ has the MSBuild server enabled by default, but I need to verify what version they're targeting and whether there are any project-specific settings that might be disabling it.\n\nThe real bottleneck is likely the implicit restore that runs before every build—using `--no-restore` when dependencies haven't changed would eliminate that overhead. For the inner development loop, `dotnet watch` is the most practical solution since it keeps the build context warm between changes.","outputTokens":1212},"id":"dca32bcf-0404-414a-9e61-02b004d85706","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:54:11.373Z","parentId":"4b844664-6ac7-4661-845e-fafbbb8f53be"}
